segments.text: Do you remember what you thought about all the problems between, well, inter-service rivalry was basically what we're talking about, wasn't it?
Well, at that time, why you're so low-ranking and so far away, why you really doesn't, it doesn't bother you at all.
It's being a second lieutenant in Hawaii and
and something that's happened at Langley Field or off of Langley Field.
I think it's just like a young child, things like that just get so far away it really doesn't attract a lot of attention.
Because you were busy in a squadron and you had all kinds of squadron jobs and community
I was system BX officer, base exchange officer, and system mess officer, and communications officer.
I don't really, at the time, really was impressed.
Okay, this is also during the 1930s, Franklin Roosevelt and the New Deal.
You had said that you were happy that you had a job, but then again you must have gone off the base.
in Texas, also in Illinois, and you must have seen some poverty and some misery.
Did the New Deal have any impact on you at all or any of Roosevelt's programs?
Did you ever think about those?
Were you political?
No.
No, in fact the first time I voted I guess was
I don't know, I think probably 63.
Because you were, well you were a resident of Texas and you always were stationed there.
Now other than having a pay cut of 10 percent, it didn't really affect you because you were in the valley.
We were in Hawaii, I was in Hawaii in

four to thirty-six and then from thirty-six to forty you were, I was at Chinook Field in Illinois and you lived in the small town of Paxton, Illinois and you lived in Hawaii and you really didn't come in contact with any poverty and your parents were
farmers and really it didn't seem that they were living any differently than when you were home, when I was home.
Because you still had, they still had plenty to eat and so it really wasn't impressive.
Okay, I'm wondering about why you decided to become interested in the bombers instead of the fighters?
Or is that the military's decision?
Well, that was a recommendation of your instructors and primaries and advanced over in
at Randolph.
I guess it's a matter of size, physical size, and whether or not you were the wiry type or the relaxed type.
If you were the wiry type, you probably would be better in fighters.
But being
relatively easy going.
Well, I guess bombers, I was very happy with bombers.
And what bombers did you learn?
Well, we had to be for the Keystone bomber and then we had a modern Martin bomber in Hawaii and then I came back to, well, Kelly when you had to transition about ten hours I think it
fighters that had been in attack and observation.
And of course when I flew the fighter, which was a little single engine aircraft, a Boeing P-12 I think it was, the crew chief almost ground me.
I didn't think I'd touch the wing, but on the first time I flew the thing, and the crew chief came out and
and rocked it up and down to the crack spar.
So the next time I got in a fighter was at Chanute, I reported in there from Hawaii.
And a guy named Spivey was operations officer and he pointed to a P-12 out there and said, you know you've had about three months at route or two months at route so you're behind and you're flying.
So he said,
you fly that thing for fifteen hours.
Well, not all at the same time, so I was very leery of that fighter because last time I'd been in it, I'd had an accident.
But anyway, I flew it and was very careful, and I didn't have any problems with it.
So while you were at Chinook, you flew everything.
You flew bombers, you had a B-18, Douglas, I guess it was made that,
and you had fighters and you had observation planes.
And moved to Scott, you did the same thing.
You flew almost everything.
What did you think of the training in the Army Air Force?
Well, I was part of it.
I spent nine years in the technical training field.
As a second lieutenant, what did you think of the quality of the training?
I mean, were they good instructors?
Well, when you
As a second lieutenant I reported to Luke Field of Wire, and then of course you had a major as a commander.
And I would say that one of the most important phases of an officer's life is who he has as a commander.
When he reports in, how much interest the commander has in you as an individual.
and his personality and the interest he takes in your career.
And then you have more senior officers, captains and first lieutenants who guide you around.
You become their wingman.
So I'd say it's really high caliber in time.
I mean the general
Major Edwards, who later became a lieutenant general, was my squaring commander, and of course he would call me by my first name, and he was very interested.
And when I went to Chanute, to a technical school, he said, now Tex, go up there and don't study, just pass.
That's all you have to do.
You don't want to be kept there as an instructor, because that's the worst thing that could happen to you, is to stay there as an instructor.
Well, I couldn't do that so when I reported in I became the base exchange officer until school started and that was about eight months ahead of time.
And then of course everybody gets to know you and then I stayed there as an instructor and then from there I became assistant director and then finally director of the technical school.
And I liked that.
In fact, from that time on, mostly I was a boss.
And I liked being boss.
You liked the education, the service school aspect of the military.
What did you like about it?
Well, I mean, it's a broadening type of thing.
And the other thing is you get a lot of management training.
And actually the military is a very efficient running operation.
And so you have, well my thesis, my master's thesis is based on career development of Air Force officers.
And I thought the Air Force did a pretty good job for me.
they sent me to technical school.
I went to, came to Randolph to learn how to fly an airplane on instruments, or blind flying as they call it.
And developed the link trainer, the link trainer programs.
So you had a lot of
of time and opportunity to develop yourself.
Sure.
And then I went to Scott and we moved the radio school from Chinook to Scott and then I was selected to go to Sioux Falls, South Dakota and I was a lieutenant colonel at the time and I got a bunch of
mostly second lieutenants.
And about sixty percent of them were sergeants who were given direct commissions as second lieutenants.
So you have yourself as lieutenant colonel and you have a bunch of second lieutenants to organize and run a school and it was just a lot of fun.
And we organized it and started
built a school from a piece of cornfield to a capacity of about 10,000 students in one year.
That I like pretty well.
I didn't really like staff work.
I moved from there to technical training command at Goldwood Field, North Carolina.
and then from there the headquarters training command.
I was at my best when I was out by myself.
When you were developing your own programs?
When I was developing my own programs and this type of thing.
Well what happened to the idea of getting in the engineer corps?
Well I said the Air Force got into your blood so you were, you just dropped that because, see, in 36
You learn to fly and I love flying.
Okay.
Tell me about your, you were the assistant director of radio technical school 1939 to 1942.
What were your duties there?
What does it mean assistant director?
Well, you had, well I think I was about second command.
I had Lud Bryan who was
who was the director and then I had myself and then I had Charlie Richards who was a senior civilian instructor.
And your job then was primarily developing expansion programs to take care of the expanding Air Force.
And so you were going around, well at one time
We were going to set up a colored technical school, and I reported to the governor of Alabama's office at the time to get secret instructions.
So, the three of us searched the southeast for some school to
to set up a technical school.
So we went to Howard University in Atlanta, I think it is.
And we thought it was a- Fisk in Atlanta?
Huh?
Fisk in Atlanta?
No, it was Howard.
Howard in Washington, D.C. isn't it?
No, that's a color school.
There is a Howard University down south someplace.
Oh, okay.
So we went to it first because we thought it was a color school.
Well, it turned out to be a white school.
So they didn't-
take to that very much.
And after visiting Emory University, we went to Tuskegee, and that's where the school was finally established.
And then we did a lot of planning on expanding the technical schools.
We opened one at Sioux Falls, South Dakota, one in Madison, Wisconsin,
one at Scott and one in Chicago, in one of the hotels, we took over one of the big hotels in Chicago.
And then we selected instructors out of the graduating classes and we took a cadre to Sioux Falls and somebody else took a cadre to
Madison, Wisconsin, and another cadre, another individual took a cadre to Chicago.
And then you start training students at Scott.
And you're training second lieutenants then?
No.
Or were you training enlisted men?
No, what you were training was enlisted men.
What you were doing, it was quite easy.
So you were getting, well, starting in 1940, you started getting a lot of people into the service.
And we had the authority to select X number of students out of the classes.
So you'd get these college graduates to be coming through as radio students, and you'd just pick them up.
Some of them, sometimes they were instructors, and had been teachers or something of this sort.
And so you pull them out of the line.
And we established a course for Chinese at Scott.
And so we went up to Chicago to the Chinese
up there, and we had found a Chinese who had his master's degree in electrical engineering.
Perfect.
He could also speak the language of the Canton, the Cantonese, or whatever it is that all our Steelers were going to be.
And so we got hired him, brought him down, trained him, started training him.
Chinese wouldn't, they said, we want to be trained by Chinese.
We would have stayed in Japan and China.
We wanted to be trained by Americans, so we had to get Mr. Depew, who was one of our senior instructors.
He would speak to them in English, and the same electrical engineer would interpret what the guy said.
Strange.
But anyway, you got into cars too.
So what you were doing is setting up training schools for radio men?
Radio, yeah.
Radio mechanics and radio operators.
The fly-in bombers and other aircraft?
The fly-in bombers and ground, take care of ground stations and all that type of thing.
How long was the course?
Sixteen weeks.
Sixteen weeks.
Sixteen weeks, normally for both the operator and the mechanic.
I bet your enrollment soared from the early 1940s when we went into the war.
Well, at Sioux Falls, South Dakota,
Enrolled 850 every week.
Wow.
850 every week.
That's incredible.
And you had to process them in and process them out.
And then of course we became known as the best radio school in the Air Force, Air Corps, because
We would select our graduates as to where they would go.
I mean, with SAC or the bombardment people in the Second Air Force who were training cadres for overseas, if they're in bombardment, we selected the best radio operators and sent them.
If they got a quarter of 50 out of the class, our first best operator would go to them.
And it backfired on us because then the commander of the guys that would run these cadres wanted all our students.
Well if they got all our students they got like everybody else was sending them.
So we kind of backed off on that one and after I got to school
And of course when we went up Sioux Falls we went out and hired a bunch of school teachers.
We hired a tremendous number of school teachers.
Women who were teaching school and brought them in, taught them radio and then they already had teaching methods and knew how to teach, how to handle students.
And so they turned out real well.
Were they civilian status?
They were civilian, yeah.
And at that time you had to, we got directives to hire X number of colored, X number of Chinese and minority groups, even in 42.
And I never had- To hire them as instructors?
As instructors, yeah.
And I never had any problem because I think you have problems when you start talking about a problem.
I mean, I just, some of the schools, they segregated the southern boys from the northern boys and put them in the colored instructor's classes.
And I said, no, we'll just put everybody in the, wherever they fall, that's where they're going to fall.
So we didn't talk about it.
And normally the colored instructors were the best anyway.
Really?
Why is that?
Why do you say that?
Well, you only hired the very best.
I see.
See, I mean, you had instructors that you were pulling out of the graduating classes.
Some of them were just a high school graduate.
But here, the colored boys, the colored instructors you were hiring, all of them had their degree from college.
Some of them had their master's degree from college.
So they were better anyway.
So we never had any problem.
Never had any problem whatsoever.
No kidding?
There was no, I mean.
No.
You didn't have very many, you didn't have any colored students going through because at that time they were all sent to Tuskegee.
Whereas you also, we had set up a system
that every two weeks you wash a student back so that you could take all levels of intelligence.

We had an army general classification test that you could predict to almost to the percentage point that would graduate on time and which one would take twice as long to get through school or what have you.
We set up a system so that every two weeks
we'd wash them back.
And if they failed, we'd just wash them back and then they'd go through.
And if they failed again, we'd wash them back again.
And we just kept them in school.
And the Army General Classification Test, I'm a great believer in your aptitude test.
I just think it shows, because we
We had thousands upon thousands of students going through the technical systems and we had IBM grading cards and established the exams so that they were equal exams.
One class didn't get a harder exam than another so you had maybe three or four different exams.
And you could tell when a guy enters almost when he's going to graduate.
But once they learned it, most of them were good at that.
I mean, they could be there to be just as good an operator as the guy who went through it the first time around.
So I think that our school system
should watch some of these boys back.
But I don't get any children back, but again you get into social problems of where a guy 14 is in the 8th grade or 6th grade and so he falls out, he drops out.
I don't know what the answer is.
Well, it seems to me then, let's get the record straight.
You had women instructors and you had black instructors and these were civilians and you had regular military
Instructors.
Instructors.
Were they officers or enlisted men?
They were enlisted men mostly.
They were enlisted men.
Yeah.

Okay, you were training enlisted men to become radio instructors and you really didn't have any problems with the women or the blacks or any of your instructors and the relationship that they had with the men.
Is that true?
No.
Well,
You always have a problem when you get girls mixed up with boys.
Oh, you mean in other words, you said that you had no problems between the whites and the blacks.
No.
But you did have problems with the women and students.
I would say that there were military problems.
I think there were.
Well, I think you have a sex problem where you get the opposite sex together.
And every once in a while, you would have whether some girl inspector or female inspector would be in some men's barracks or something of this sort.
But it wasn't a major problem.
Because most of the part they were very, very good.
And they were very, very conscientious and they thought they were doing their job.
I mean, doing their job for the service.
And we had quite a few of them.
I would say about a third of our instructors were women.
And how many, what percentage were black?
Oh, maybe three or four, not very many.
Three or four percent?
Yeah, three or four, yeah.
And how many instructors did you have?
Oh, maybe I'd say about 400.
And this is just up at Sioux Falls?
Yeah, up at Sioux Falls.
Okay, now you were the director of radar and radio, and this is technical schools, and this was at Sioux Falls?
Yeah, it was a radio school.
It was pure and simple a radio school.
Why did they call it radar and radio technical school then?
Well, see, we establishedsee, I think I'd gone over to England.
We had
a radar school established at Scott, which was what we call a pathfinder.
There was a radar bombing school.
I took a trip after I left Sioux Falls and got to the headquarters of Technical Training Command in Fort Worth.
I took a 90 day tour of England to study the radar systems and
air-sea rescue systems and how our students were doing.
And when I got back, I went down to Boca Raton, Florida to run a radar school.
Oh, I see.
The radar was separate from the radio.
Okay, then you were at Sioux Falls from, could you tell me what years then you were there as the director?
Okay, okay.
So in 42 to 43 you were the director of the radio school up at...
At Sioux Falls and then 44 and 43 to 45, you were the director of the radar school down in Florida.
OK, well, were there differences?
Were there different scopes or different problems that you had at these two schools?
Well, see, at the radio schools, we had established a system so that if you're going to talk about a spoon, everybody would have a spoon in his hand.
If you're talking about a glass, if you're talking about a radio tube, well everybody would have a tube in his hand.
So that your method of instruction was very, very practical.
So when that idea was put out by General Weaver, then we grabbed it and ran with it up to Sioux Falls, South Dakota.
Now down at Keesler, it was an airplane mechanics school, and then after I got to his headquarters at Norwood Field, we went down there one time and they were still teaching the same theoretical.
I mean they were gum beating is what I'd call it, up before blackboard.
So it was a practical application in Sioux Falls with a radio school.
With a radar school, it was theoretical.
Getting to the mechanical school.
So we were ordered, well, we spent the night there, and he ordered every chair out of every classroom to be piled up outside.
And then the next day he went back, and all the students were standing up.
And so that's how he got...
the mechanical school on a practical basis.
His idea was that if a guy was learning about engines, then he had to have an engine to work on.
And if he unscrewed a nut off of an engine, well then he'd lay it down here.
That was nut number one.
That nut would be number two.
And then when that nut went back on, it went back on the same thread as it came off of.
Now this is kind of ridiculous,
But anyway, so after that, why that became practical?
Well, the radar school was the most difficult to get into a practical method of instruction.
And I was sent down to Boca Time, Florida to change it from a theoretical school to a practical school.
And you had just returned from England?
I had just returned from England to find out that our radar students were very good theorists, but they had never seen the equipment before.
So I went down there.
You mean your radar instructors?
No, the radar students who were being graduated.
They knew the theory, but they didn't know how to work on the equipment.
You're only out selecting me, and I went down there to make this into a practical school.
And of course, you get into the situation that you're the boss, but all the people who work there are theorists.
And they just say, Colonel, there's no way of doing it that way.
And I say, well, there must be some way.
So I started selecting the
the combat crew officers, people who had gone to England and completed their 30 missions or 50 missions, whatever it was, and had come back to the States, and most of them were college graduates,
So we put them through the radar school, and I started selecting them off the base.
And then every time a guy would say he can't do it, I would say, I would put him on the shipping order.
Next time I get a directive to ship a radar officer off, I'd ship him.
